{"title_page": "Nitish Bharadwaj", "text_new": "{{COI|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Nitish Bharadwaj\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_place        = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], India\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=y|1963|6|2}}\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Actor|director|[[Film producer|producer]]|screenwriter}}\n| yearsactive        = 1987 \u2013 present\n| spouse             = srimita bharadwaj\n| residence          = Mumbai\n}}\n\n'''Nitish Bharadwaj''' (born 2 June 1963) is an Indian film actor, director, screenwriter, producer<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinestaan.com/people/nitish-bhardwaj-61758|title=Nitish Bhardwaj movies, filmography, biography and songs - Cinestaan.com|website=Cinestaan|access-date=2019-08-08}}</ref>, and former [[Member of parliament, Lok Sabha|member of Parliament]] in [[Lok Sabha]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2002/20020317/spectrum/main7.htm |title=Mythologicals in Their Modern Avatar |last=Patil |first=Vimla |date=17 March 2002 |website=Spectrum |publisher=The Sunday Tribune |access-date=5 April 2016}}</ref> He is best known for his role as [[Lord Krishna]] in [[B. R. Chopra]]'s television series ''[[Mahabharat (1988 TV series)|Mahabharat]]'', as well as for his portrayal of several [[Avatar]]s of [[Vishnu]] in some of Chopra's other works, such as ''[[Vishnu Puran (TV series)|Vishnu Puran]]''.<ref name=\"Pandit\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-09-05/news-interviews/41800792_1_marathi-film-film-yaksha-film-industry |title=Nitish Bharadwaj dons the hat of a director |last=Pandit |first=Shruti |date=10 September 2013 |work=The Times of India |accessdate=22 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tv/news/Comparisons-with-Nitish-Bharadwaj-are-most-welcome-Saurabh-Raaj-Jain/articleshow/24253763.cms? |title=Comparisons with Nitish Bharadwaj are most welcome: Saurabh Raaj Jain |last=Trivedi |first=Tanvi |date=17 October 2013 |work=The Times of India |access-date=5 April 2016}}</ref> His debut directorial film in Marathi titled ''Pitruroon'' has won him accolades from both the audiences and critics and he now focuses on his film career entirely through screenwriting, directing and acting.\n\n==Career==\n===Theatre and radio===\nBorn in Marathi Brahaman Bhardwaj gotra, Nitish started his arts career with his training in Marathi theatre as a Director, under many stalwarts such as Late Sudha Karmarkar, Dr. Kashinath Ghanekar and Prabhakar Panshikar. He then moved on to Professional Marathi theatre with Sai Paranjapye and later shifted to Hindi theatre on sound advice from his friend Ravi Baswani. Ravi was, in fact, instrumental in getting Nitish from Marathi to the nation-wide Hindi arena and Nitish has always acknowledged Ravi's contribution to his life. He worked with a thespian of Hindi theatre named Dinesh Thakur and performed in many of his plays till 1987. He later did a Hindi mythological play titled ''Chakravyuh'', in which he reappears as Lord Krishna, the role he has mastered in the old ''Mahabharat''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mumbaitheatreguide.com/dramas/hindi/09-hindi-play-preview-chakravyuh.asp#|title=CHAKRAVYUH Hindi Play/Drama - www.MumbaiTheatreGuide.com|website=www.mumbaitheatreguide.com|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> Though the play depicts the story of Abhimanyu's martyrdom, it brings out various issues out of the same story which are relevant to today's times. ''Chakravyuh'' is one of the most successful plays of Hindi Theatre in 2015 and  has already had around 75 showings across India, including some prestigious theatre festivals like the Kala Ghoda Festival, Mumbai. Nitish also performed in a musical theatre production titled ''[[Motiroti|Moti Roti Patli Chunni]]'' (1993), with a renowned theatre in London (UK)  named \"Theatre Royal Stratford East\". This play won the \"London Time Out Dance & Performance Award\" and toured across Britain and Canada.\n\nNitish also did 2 radio shows for BBC Radio 4 (London, UK), namely ''Bhagvad Geeta'' and ''Ramayan''. He was nominated for the \"Sony Radio award\" for ''Ramayan'' in the UK in 1995.\n\n===Television and films===\nNitish Bharadwaj has starred in many [[Marathi cinema|Marathi]] movies such as ''Khatyal Sass Natal Soon'', ''Nasheebwan'', ''Anapekshit'', ''Pasanta Ahe Mulgi'', ''Trishagi'' (with Nana Patekar) and the highly acclaimed [[Malayalam]] movie ''[[Njan Gandharvan]]'', (1991) directed by [[P. Padmarajan]]. He directed a historical TV serial titled ''Gita Rahasya'', ''Apraadhi'' for Star TV and a few documentary films.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/election/1999/sep/10nitish.htm |title=The Rediff Election Interview / Nitish Bharadwaj |last=Ashraf |first=Syed Firdaus |date=10 September 1999 |website=Rediff on the Net |access-date=5 April 2016}}</ref> After ''Njan Gandharvan'', Padmarajan was planning a film with [[Mohanlal]] and Bharadwaj in lead roles, but he died before it could materialise. In a later interview in 2019, Bharadwaj said that, if that film had happened, he might have settled in [[Kerala]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Kumar|first=K. P. Nijeesh|title=Padmarajan's demise made me to exit from mollywood, says 'Njan Gandharvan' actor|url=https://english.mathrubhumi.com/news/kerala/padmarajan-s-demise-made-me-to-exit-from-mollywood-says-njan-gandharvan-actor-1.3955257|accessdate=16 July 2019|work=[[Mathrubhumi]]|date=14 July 2019}}</ref> He judged a Marathi dance reality show on [[ETV Marathi]]; ''Jallosh Survanayugacha'', with Sudha Chandran and Ramesh Deo. Bharadwaj made his film direction debut in 2013 with a Marathi film starring Tanuja, Suhas Joshi and Sachin Khedekar titled ''Pitruroon''. The film is based on a novella by Sudha Murthy. The film was acclaimed by both the critics and audiences. ''Pitruroon'' received many nominations and awards, and also gave Bharadwaj the prestigious Maharashtra State Film Award as the second Best Director of 2013.<ref name=\"Pandit\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://rangmarathi.com/first-look-of-nitish-bharadwajs-pitruroon/ |title=First look of Nitish Bharadwaj's Pitruroon |date=23 August 2013 |website=Rangmarathi |access-date=6 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/krishna-s-confessions/1091171/ |title=Krishna's Confessions |last=Swamy |first=Rohan |date=21 March 2013 |website=The Indian Express |access-date=6 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-02-16/news-interviews/37120048_1_marathi-cinema-quality-films-short-films |title=Nitish Bharadwaj ropes in Tanuja his directorial debut |last=Deshmukh |first=Gayatri |date=16 February 2013 |work=The Times of India |access-date=5 April 2016}}</ref> Bharadwaj played [[Krishna]] at the age of 23 and became an overnight star.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-mahabharats-krishna-is-back-tv/20130522.htm |title=I DID NOT want to play Krishna in 'Mahabharat' |last=N |first=Patcy |date=22 May 2013 |website=Rediff Movies |access-date=6 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-reader-s-pick-the-25-greatest-characters-on-indian-tv/20120918.htm#19 |title=Reader's Pick: The 25 GREATEST characters on Indian TV |last=Verma |first=Sukanya |date=18 September 2012 |website=Rediff Movies |access-date=6 April 2016}}</ref> Nitish Bharadwaj has also made appearances in movies including [[Mohenjo Daro (film)|Mohenjo Daro]] and [[Kedarnath (film)|Kedarnath]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Nitish-Bharadwaj-My-role-in-Mohenjo-Daro-has-given-me-an-opportunity-to-explore-human-emotions/articleshow/53569751.cms|title=Nitish Bharadwaj: My role in 'Mohenjo Daro' has given me an opportunity to explore human emotions - Times of India|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n\n===Politics===\nBharadwaj contested the parliamentary elections from [[Jamshedpur]] and [[Rajgarh (Lok Sabha constituency)|Rajgarh]] (in [[Madhya Pradesh]]) as a [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) candidate and was elected to [[Lok Sabha]] as a Member of Parliament from [[Jamshedpur (Lok Sabha constituency)|Jamshedpur]] in 1996, by defeating veteran Inder Singh Namdhari.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/entertai/1998/feb/12bjp.htm |title=Any party which wants to rule India has to be secular in its true sense |last=Masih |first=Archana |date=12 February 1998 |website=Rediff on the Net |access-date=6 April 2016}}</ref> He lost to Laxman Singh (brother of then chief minister of Madhya Pradesh, [[Digvijaya Singh]]) in the 1999 Lok Sabha elections.\nHe also worked in BJP's organisational unit of Madhya Pradesh and was also its Spokesperson for a while, till he voluntarily retired from active politics.\n\n==Personal life==\nNitish was born to late Janardan C. Upadhye, a Senior Advocate of Bombay High Court and a veteran labour lawyer. He was also a close aide of George Fernandes in the labour movement in the 60s and 70s. Nitish's mother, the late Sadhana Upadhye, was the Head of Marathi Literature department in Wilson College, Mumbai. She was an exponent of the Bhagvad Geeta and Dnyaneshwari, the knowledge of which she imparted to Nitish from childhood.\n\nIn 1991, Nitish Bharadwaj married Monisha Patil, daughter of [[Vimla Patil]], then editor of ''[[Femina (India)|Femina]]''. They have two children and divorced in 2005.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1041114/asp/look/story_3984806.asp |title=Nitish, Nitish, burning bright |last=Roy |first=Amit |date=14 November 2004 |work=The Telegraph |location=Calcutta, India |access-date=6 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/entertai/1998/feb/13bjp1.htm |title=For how many years do you want the adivasis to wear their traditional finery and dance for you? |last= |first= |date=13 February 1998 |website=Rediff on the Net |access-date=6 April 2016}}</ref> Monisha now lives in London with their children. Bharadwaj married Smita Gate, an IAS officer (1992 batch) from Madhya Pradesh cadre, in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://archive.mid-day.com/news/2010/jan/110110-Sanjay-Dutt-Samajwadi-Party-politicians.htm |title=Sanjay Dutt resigs from Samajwadi Party |last=Singh |first=Varun |date=11 January 2010 |website=Mid-day |access-date=6 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n;Films\n* ''[[Trishagni]]'' (1988) (with Nana Patekar) <ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8y8vN9A14nkC&pg=PT578&dq=trishagni+1988&hl=en&sa=X&ei=url_UfH9DMPXrQfAtIBY&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAQ |title=Encyclopedia of Hindi Cinema |last2=Nihalani |first2=Govind |last3=Chatterjee |first3=Saibal |publisher=Popular Prakashan |year=2003 |isbn=8179910660 |series=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica (India) |page=554 |author=Gulzar |authorlink=Gulzar}}</ref>\n* ''[[Njan Gandharvan]]'' (1991, Malayalam)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.prd.kerala.gov.in/stateawards2.htm |title=State Film Awards |date=1990 |website=Information & Public Relations Department (I&PRD) |access-date=6 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303234213/http://www.prd.kerala.gov.in/stateawards2.htm |archivedate=3 March 2016 }}</ref>\n* ''[[Sangeet (1992 film)|Sangeet]]'' (1992) (with Madhuri Dixit)\n* ''Prem Daan'' (1991) (with Khushboo)\n* ''[[Prem Shakti]]'' (1994) (with Govinda, Karishma kapoor)\n* ''Nacehe Nagin Gali Gali'' (1991) (with Meenakshi Seshadri)\n* ''Khatyal Sasu Nathal Soon'' (1987) (with Varsha Usgaonkar)\n* ''Pasant Aahe Mulgi'' (1989) (with Varsha Usgaonkar)\n* ''Tujhi Majhi Jamli Jodi'' (1990) (with Nivedita Joshi)\n* ''Nashibwaan'' (1988) (with Alka Kubal)\n* ''[[Pitruroon]]'' (2013) (Writer-Director)\n* ''[[Mahabharat Aur Barbareek|Mahabharat Aur Barbareek]]'' (2013) as [[Krishna]]\n* ''[[Mohenjo Daro (film)|Mohenjo Daro]]'' (2016) (with Hritik Roshan)\n* ''Yaksh'' (awaiting worldwide release) (title role)\n* ''[[Kedarnath (film)|Kedarnath]]'' (2018)\n\n;Television\n* ''[[Mahabharat (1988 TV series)|Mahabharat]]'' (1988)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ibnlive.com/photogallery/tv/25-years-of-br-chopras-mahabharata-do-you-remember-these-iconic-characters-903942.html |title=25 years of BR Chopra's 'Mahabharata': Do you remember these iconic characters? |date=23 April 2013 |website=IBN Live |publisher=CNN |access-date=6 April 2016}}</ref>\n* ''[[Geeta Rahasya(1999)|Geeta Rahasya]]'' (producer-Director-Co writer) (with Irrfan Khan)\n* ''[[Vishnu Puran (TV series)|Vishnu Puran]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Ramayan (2002 TV series)|Ramayan]]'' (2003) with Smriti Irani as Seeta\n* ''[[Man Mein Hai Visshwas]]'' (2006-2007, presenter)\n* ''Ajab Gajab Ghar Jamai'' (2014, Krishna)\n\n==Award nominations==\n* Best Director for ''Pitruroon'', Screen Awards, 2014\n\n==Awards==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=February 2018}}\n* Best Screenplay Writer for Marathi feature film, ''Pitruroon'', Sahyadri Film Awards, 2014\n* 2nd Best Director for ''Pitruroon'', [[Maharashtra State Film Awards]], 2014\n* 2nd Best Film for ''Pitruroon'', Maharashtra State Film Awards, 2014\n* Tanuja and Sachin Khedekar won Best Actor Screen Awards for Nitish's film ''Pitruroon'', January 2014\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0080232}}\n* [https://www.facebook.com/nitishbharadwaj.krishna Official Facebook page]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bharadwaj, Nitish}}\n[[Category:Indian male television actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:11th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:Indian television presenters]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Jharkhand]]\n[[Category:Indian actor-politicians]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Jharkhand]]\n", "text_old": "{{COI|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Nitish Bharadwaj\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_place        = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], India\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=y|1963|6|2}}\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Actor|director|[[Film producer|producer]]|screenwriter}}\n| yearsactive        = 1987 \u2013 present\n| spouse             = \n| residence          = Mumbai\n}}\n\n'''Nitish Bharadwaj''' (born 2 June 1963) is an Indian film actor, director, screenwriter, producer<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinestaan.com/people/nitish-bhardwaj-61758|title=Nitish Bhardwaj movies, filmography, biography and songs - Cinestaan.com|website=Cinestaan|access-date=2019-08-08}}</ref>, and former [[Member of parliament, Lok Sabha|member of Parliament]] in [[Lok Sabha]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2002/20020317/spectrum/main7.htm |title=Mythologicals in Their Modern Avatar |last=Patil |first=Vimla |date=17 March 2002 |website=Spectrum |publisher=The Sunday Tribune |access-date=5 April 2016}}</ref> He is best known for his role as [[Lord Krishna]] in [[B. R. Chopra]]'s television series ''[[Mahabharat (1988 TV series)|Mahabharat]]'', as well as for his portrayal of several [[Avatar]]s of [[Vishnu]] in some of Chopra's other works, such as ''[[Vishnu Puran (TV series)|Vishnu Puran]]''.<ref name=\"Pandit\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-09-05/news-interviews/41800792_1_marathi-film-film-yaksha-film-industry |title=Nitish Bharadwaj dons the hat of a director |last=Pandit |first=Shruti |date=10 September 2013 |work=The Times of India |accessdate=22 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tv/news/Comparisons-with-Nitish-Bharadwaj-are-most-welcome-Saurabh-Raaj-Jain/articleshow/24253763.cms? |title=Comparisons with Nitish Bharadwaj are most welcome: Saurabh Raaj Jain |last=Trivedi |first=Tanvi |date=17 October 2013 |work=The Times of India |access-date=5 April 2016}}</ref> His debut directorial film in Marathi titled ''Pitruroon'' has won him accolades from both the audiences and critics and he now focuses on his film career entirely through screenwriting, directing and acting.\n\n==Career==\n===Theatre and radio===\nBorn in Marathi Brahaman Bhardwaj gotra, Nitish started his arts career with his training in Marathi theatre as a Director, under many stalwarts such as Late Sudha Karmarkar, Dr. Kashinath Ghanekar and Prabhakar Panshikar. He then moved on to Professional Marathi theatre with Sai Paranjapye and later shifted to Hindi theatre on sound advice from his friend Ravi Baswani. Ravi was, in fact, instrumental in getting Nitish from Marathi to the nation-wide Hindi arena and Nitish has always acknowledged Ravi's contribution to his life. He worked with a thespian of Hindi theatre named Dinesh Thakur and performed in many of his plays till 1987. He later did a Hindi mythological play titled ''Chakravyuh'', in which he reappears as Lord Krishna, the role he has mastered in the old ''Mahabharat''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mumbaitheatreguide.com/dramas/hindi/09-hindi-play-preview-chakravyuh.asp#|title=CHAKRAVYUH Hindi Play/Drama - www.MumbaiTheatreGuide.com|website=www.mumbaitheatreguide.com|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> Though the play depicts the story of Abhimanyu's martyrdom, it brings out various issues out of the same story which are relevant to today's times. ''Chakravyuh'' is one of the most successful plays of Hindi Theatre in 2015 and  has already had around 75 showings across India, including some prestigious theatre festivals like the Kala Ghoda Festival, Mumbai. Nitish also performed in a musical theatre production titled ''[[Motiroti|Moti Roti Patli Chunni]]'' (1993), with a renowned theatre in London (UK)  named \"Theatre Royal Stratford East\". This play won the \"London Time Out Dance & Performance Award\" and toured across Britain and Canada.\n\nNitish also did 2 radio shows for BBC Radio 4 (London, UK), namely ''Bhagvad Geeta'' and ''Ramayan''. He was nominated for the \"Sony Radio award\" for ''Ramayan'' in the UK in 1995.\n\n===Television and films===\nNitish Bharadwaj has starred in many [[Marathi cinema|Marathi]] movies such as ''Khatyal Sass Natal Soon'', ''Nasheebwan'', ''Anapekshit'', ''Pasanta Ahe Mulgi'', ''Trishagi'' (with Nana Patekar) and the highly acclaimed [[Malayalam]] movie ''[[Njan Gandharvan]]'', (1991) directed by [[P. Padmarajan]]. He directed a historical TV serial titled ''Gita Rahasya'', ''Apraadhi'' for Star TV and a few documentary films.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/election/1999/sep/10nitish.htm |title=The Rediff Election Interview / Nitish Bharadwaj |last=Ashraf |first=Syed Firdaus |date=10 September 1999 |website=Rediff on the Net |access-date=5 April 2016}}</ref> After ''Njan Gandharvan'', Padmarajan was planning a film with [[Mohanlal]] and Bharadwaj in lead roles, but he died before it could materialise. In a later interview in 2019, Bharadwaj said that, if that film had happened, he might have settled in [[Kerala]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Kumar|first=K. P. Nijeesh|title=Padmarajan's demise made me to exit from mollywood, says 'Njan Gandharvan' actor|url=https://english.mathrubhumi.com/news/kerala/padmarajan-s-demise-made-me-to-exit-from-mollywood-says-njan-gandharvan-actor-1.3955257|accessdate=16 July 2019|work=[[Mathrubhumi]]|date=14 July 2019}}</ref> He judged a Marathi dance reality show on [[ETV Marathi]]; ''Jallosh Survanayugacha'', with Sudha Chandran and Ramesh Deo. Bharadwaj made his film direction debut in 2013 with a Marathi film starring Tanuja, Suhas Joshi and Sachin Khedekar titled ''Pitruroon''. The film is based on a novella by Sudha Murthy. The film was acclaimed by both the critics and audiences. ''Pitruroon'' received many nominations and awards, and also gave Bharadwaj the prestigious Maharashtra State Film Award as the second Best Director of 2013.<ref name=\"Pandit\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://rangmarathi.com/first-look-of-nitish-bharadwajs-pitruroon/ |title=First look of Nitish Bharadwaj's Pitruroon |date=23 August 2013 |website=Rangmarathi |access-date=6 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/krishna-s-confessions/1091171/ |title=Krishna's Confessions |last=Swamy |first=Rohan |date=21 March 2013 |website=The Indian Express |access-date=6 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-02-16/news-interviews/37120048_1_marathi-cinema-quality-films-short-films |title=Nitish Bharadwaj ropes in Tanuja his directorial debut |last=Deshmukh |first=Gayatri |date=16 February 2013 |work=The Times of India |access-date=5 April 2016}}</ref> Bharadwaj played [[Krishna]] at the age of 23 and became an overnight star.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-mahabharats-krishna-is-back-tv/20130522.htm |title=I DID NOT want to play Krishna in 'Mahabharat' |last=N |first=Patcy |date=22 May 2013 |website=Rediff Movies |access-date=6 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-reader-s-pick-the-25-greatest-characters-on-indian-tv/20120918.htm#19 |title=Reader's Pick: The 25 GREATEST characters on Indian TV |last=Verma |first=Sukanya |date=18 September 2012 |website=Rediff Movies |access-date=6 April 2016}}</ref> Nitish Bharadwaj has also made appearances in movies including [[Mohenjo Daro (film)|Mohenjo Daro]] and [[Kedarnath (film)|Kedarnath]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Nitish-Bharadwaj-My-role-in-Mohenjo-Daro-has-given-me-an-opportunity-to-explore-human-emotions/articleshow/53569751.cms|title=Nitish Bharadwaj: My role in 'Mohenjo Daro' has given me an opportunity to explore human emotions - Times of India|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n\n===Politics===\nBharadwaj contested the parliamentary elections from [[Jamshedpur]] and [[Rajgarh (Lok Sabha constituency)|Rajgarh]] (in [[Madhya Pradesh]]) as a [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) candidate and was elected to [[Lok Sabha]] as a Member of Parliament from [[Jamshedpur (Lok Sabha constituency)|Jamshedpur]] in 1996, by defeating veteran Inder Singh Namdhari.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/entertai/1998/feb/12bjp.htm |title=Any party which wants to rule India has to be secular in its true sense |last=Masih |first=Archana |date=12 February 1998 |website=Rediff on the Net |access-date=6 April 2016}}</ref> He lost to Laxman Singh (brother of then chief minister of Madhya Pradesh, [[Digvijaya Singh]]) in the 1999 Lok Sabha elections.\nHe also worked in BJP's organisational unit of Madhya Pradesh and was also its Spokesperson for a while, till he voluntarily retired from active politics.\n\n==Personal life==\nNitish was born to late Janardan C. Upadhye, a Senior Advocate of Bombay High Court and a veteran labour lawyer. He was also a close aide of George Fernandes in the labour movement in the 60s and 70s. Nitish's mother, the late Sadhana Upadhye, was the Head of Marathi Literature department in Wilson College, Mumbai. She was an exponent of the Bhagvad Geeta and Dnyaneshwari, the knowledge of which she imparted to Nitish from childhood.\n\nIn 1991, Nitish Bharadwaj married Monisha Patil, daughter of [[Vimla Patil]], then editor of ''[[Femina (India)|Femina]]''. They have two children and divorced in 2005.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1041114/asp/look/story_3984806.asp |title=Nitish, Nitish, burning bright |last=Roy |first=Amit |date=14 November 2004 |work=The Telegraph |location=Calcutta, India |access-date=6 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/entertai/1998/feb/13bjp1.htm |title=For how many years do you want the adivasis to wear their traditional finery and dance for you? |last= |first= |date=13 February 1998 |website=Rediff on the Net |access-date=6 April 2016}}</ref> Monisha now lives in London with their children. Bharadwaj married Smita Gate, an IAS officer (1992 batch) from Madhya Pradesh cadre, in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://archive.mid-day.com/news/2010/jan/110110-Sanjay-Dutt-Samajwadi-Party-politicians.htm |title=Sanjay Dutt resigs from Samajwadi Party |last=Singh |first=Varun |date=11 January 2010 |website=Mid-day |access-date=6 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n;Films\n* ''[[Trishagni]]'' (1988) (with Nana Patekar) <ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8y8vN9A14nkC&pg=PT578&dq=trishagni+1988&hl=en&sa=X&ei=url_UfH9DMPXrQfAtIBY&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAQ |title=Encyclopedia of Hindi Cinema |last2=Nihalani |first2=Govind |last3=Chatterjee |first3=Saibal |publisher=Popular Prakashan |year=2003 |isbn=8179910660 |series=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica (India) |page=554 |author=Gulzar |authorlink=Gulzar}}</ref>\n* ''[[Njan Gandharvan]]'' (1991, Malayalam)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.prd.kerala.gov.in/stateawards2.htm |title=State Film Awards |date=1990 |website=Information & Public Relations Department (I&PRD) |access-date=6 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303234213/http://www.prd.kerala.gov.in/stateawards2.htm |archivedate=3 March 2016 }}</ref>\n* ''[[Sangeet (1992 film)|Sangeet]]'' (1992) (with Madhuri Dixit)\n* ''Prem Daan'' (1991) (with Khushboo)\n* ''[[Prem Shakti]]'' (1994) (with Govinda, Karishma kapoor)\n* ''Nacehe Nagin Gali Gali'' (1991) (with Meenakshi Seshadri)\n* ''Khatyal Sasu Nathal Soon'' (1987) (with Varsha Usgaonkar)\n* ''Pasant Aahe Mulgi'' (1989) (with Varsha Usgaonkar)\n* ''Tujhi Majhi Jamli Jodi'' (1990) (with Nivedita Joshi)\n* ''Nashibwaan'' (1988) (with Alka Kubal)\n* ''[[Pitruroon]]'' (2013) (Writer-Director)\n* ''[[Mahabharat Aur Barbareek|Mahabharat Aur Barbareek]]'' (2013) as [[Krishna]]\n* ''[[Mohenjo Daro (film)|Mohenjo Daro]]'' (2016) (with Hritik Roshan)\n* '